{"title_page": "The Adventures of El Ballo", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=December 2012}}\n{{Notability|Products|date=December 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = The Adventures of El Ballo\n|image = El-Ballo-software-icon.png\n|alt = Software icon for The Adventures of El Ballo\n|developer = ProRattaFactor\n|publisher = [[Ambrosia Software]]\n|designer = \n|engine = \n|released = September 19, 2005<ref name=\"ambrosia_faq_release_date\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ambrosiasw.com/support/faqs/products/el-ballo/When-was-el-Ballo-first-released |title=When was el Ballo first released? |publisher=[[Ambrosia Software]] |date=2005-09-30 |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref>\n|genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n|modes = [[Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[Mac OS]], [[Mac OS X]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Adventures of El Ballo''''' is a 2D [[side-scrolling]] platform game for  Mac OS 9 and X released by [[Ambrosia Software]] on September 19, 2005.<ref name=\"ambrosia_faq_release_date\"/> It focuses on blatant, crude humor and mild animated nudity and includes [[parental controls]] to disable some content.<ref name=\"macworld\">{{cite web |url=http://www.macworld.com/article/1051310/adelba.html |title=The Adventures of El Ballo |publisher=[[MacWorld]] |author=Cohen, Peter |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref> The game was poorly received by Macintosh publications.\n\n==Plot==\nThe game takes place on the planet Testicular which is located in the \"Circular Assmosphere\" [[solar system]].<ref name=\"img_review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.insidemacgames.com/reviews/view.php?ID=651 |title=Inside Mac Games Review: El Ballo |publisher=[[Inside Mac Games]] |author=Cloudfelter, Bryan |date=2005-10-31 |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref> Testicular is populated by an unsanitary but peace-loving and playful alien race.<ref name=\"img_review\"/> The evil Dr. Cough is out to cleanse the planet Testicular and to make the inhabitants give up their love of nakedness in favor of being clothed.<ref name=\"img_review\"/><ref name=\"ambrosia_sw\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ambrosiasw.com/games/elballo/ |title=el Ballo |publisher=[[Ambrosia Software]] |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref> El Ballo, one of the aliens who lives on Testicular with such companions as \"Butts\" and \"Boobs,\" must take on the [[Chlorine]] Copters, Mic the Mop, and other henchmen of Dr. Cough before heading to the castle where El Ballo must deal with the evil doctor.<ref name=\"macworld\"/><ref name=\"ambrosia_sw\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nIn ''[[MacWorld]]'', Peter Cohen complimented the game's art and music but felt that the game play itself lacked fun.<ref name=\"macworld\"/> ''[[Inside Mac Games]]'' gave El Ballo a 3.75 out of 10 rating, stating that the game play was unexciting and very easy though the game's plot was unique.<ref name=\"img_review\"/> Also mentioned by Inside Mac Games was the issue of the game's adult theme posing concerns for parents, given the inclusion of sexual references in certain parts of the game and that the game's parental control feature was easy to bypass.<ref name=\"img_review\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ambrosiasw.com/games/elballo/ el Ballo] at Ambrosia Software\n* [http://www.ambrosiasw.com/support/faqs/products/el-ballo/ el Ballo FAQ] at Ambrosia Software\n\n{{Ambrosia Software}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adventures of El Ballo, The}}\n[[Category:2005 video games]]\n[[Category:Ambrosia Software games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Mac OS games]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n\n\n{{Platform-videogame-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=December 2012}}\n{{Notability|Products|date=December 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = The Adventures of El Ballo\n|image = El-Ballo-software-icon.png\n|alt = Software icon for The Adventures of El Ballo\n|developer = ProRattaFactor\n|publisher = [[Ambrosia Software]]\n|designer = \n|engine = \n|released = September 19, 2005<ref name=\"ambrosia_faq_release_date\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ambrosiasw.com/support/faqs/products/el-ballo/When-was-el-Ballo-first-released |title=When was el Ballo first released? |publisher=[[Ambrosia Software]] |date=2005-09-30 |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref>\n|genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n|modes = [[Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[Mac OS]], [[Mac OS X]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Adventures of El Ballo''''' is a 2D [[side-scrolling]] platormn game for  Mac OS 9 and X released by [[Ambrosia Software]] on September 19, 2005.<ref name=\"ambrosia_faq_release_date\"/> It focuses on blatant, crude humor and mild animated nudity and includes [[parental controls]] to disable some content.<ref name=\"macworld\">{{cite web |url=http://www.macworld.com/article/1051310/adelba.html |title=The Adventures of El Ballo |publisher=[[MacWorld]] |author=Cohen, Peter |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref> The game was poorly received by Macintosh publications.\n\n==Plot==\nThe game takes place on the planet Testicular which is located in the \"Circular Assmosphere\" [[solar system]].<ref name=\"img_review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.insidemacgames.com/reviews/view.php?ID=651 |title=Inside Mac Games Review: El Ballo |publisher=[[Inside Mac Games]] |author=Cloudfelter, Bryan |date=2005-10-31 |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref> Testicular is populated by an unsanitary but peace-loving and playful alien race.<ref name=\"img_review\"/> The evil Dr. Cough is out to cleanse the planet Testicular and to make the inhabitants give up their love of nakedness in favor of being clothed.<ref name=\"img_review\"/><ref name=\"ambrosia_sw\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ambrosiasw.com/games/elballo/ |title=el Ballo |publisher=[[Ambrosia Software]] |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref> El Ballo, one of the aliens who lives on Testicular with such companions as \"Butts\" and \"Boobs,\" must take on the [[Chlorine]] Copters, Mic the Mop, and other henchmen of Dr. Cough before heading to the castle where El Ballo must deal with the evil doctor.<ref name=\"macworld\"/><ref name=\"ambrosia_sw\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nIn ''[[MacWorld]]'', Peter Cohen complimented the game's art and music but felt that the game play itself lacked fun.<ref name=\"macworld\"/> ''[[Inside Mac Games]]'' gave El Ballo a 3.75 out of 10 rating, stating that the game play was unexciting and very easy though the game's plot was unique.<ref name=\"img_review\"/> Also mentioned by Inside Mac Games was the issue of the game's adult theme posing concerns for parents, given the inclusion of sexual references in certain parts of the game and that the game's parental control feature was easy to bypass.<ref name=\"img_review\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ambrosiasw.com/games/elballo/ el Ballo] at Ambrosia Software\n* [http://www.ambrosiasw.com/support/faqs/products/el-ballo/ el Ballo FAQ] at Ambrosia Software\n\n{{Ambrosia Software}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adventures of El Ballo, The}}\n[[Category:2005 video games]]\n[[Category:Ambrosia Software games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Mac OS games]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n\n\n{{Platform-videogame-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dgpop", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Adventures_of_El_Ballo"}
{"title_page": "Antonio L\u00f3pez Habas", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish football player/manager}}\n{{spanish name 2|L\u00f3pez|Habas}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Antonio Habas\n| image =Antonio L\u00f3pez Habas.jpg\n| caption =\n| fullname = Antonio L\u00f3pez Habas\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|5|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Pozoblanco]], Spain\n| height = {{convert|1.70|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] (manager)\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1976\u20131977\n| years2 = 1977\u20131978\n| years3 = 1978\u20131980\n| years4 = 1980\u20131982\n| years5 = 1982\u20131985\n| years6 = 1985\u20131986\n| clubs1 = [[CD Pozoblanco|Pozoblanco]]\n| clubs2 = [[Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico|Sevilla B]]\n| clubs3 = [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]\n| clubs4 = [[Burgos CF (I)|Burgos]]\n| clubs5 = [[Real Murcia|Murcia]]\n| clubs6 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| caps1 =\n| caps2 =\n| caps3 = 8\n| caps4 = 45\n| caps5 = 74\n| caps6 = 0\n| totalcaps = \n| goals1 =\n| goals2 =\n| goals3 = 0\n| goals4 = 14\n| goals5 = 11\n| goals6 = 0\n| totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 =\n| nationalcaps1 =\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| manageryears1 = 1990\u20131991\n| manageryears2 = 1991\u20131992\n| manageryears3 = 1992\u20131993\n| manageryears4 = 1993\u20131994\n| manageryears5 = 1994\u20131995\n| manageryears6 = 1995\u20131996\n| manageryears7 = 1995\u20131997\n| manageryears8 = 1998\n| manageryears9 = 2000\u20132001\n| manageryears10 = 2001\u20132003\n| manageryears11 = 2005\n| manageryears12 = 2005\n| manageryears13 = 2007\u20132008\n| manageryears14 = 2008\n| manageryears15 = 2009\u20132010\n| manageryears16 = 2010\u20132011\n| manageryears17 = 2012\u20132013\n| manageryears18 = 2014\u20132016\n| manageryears19 = 2016\u20132017\n| manageryears20 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|Atl\u00e9tico Madrile\u00f1o]]\n| managerclubs2 = [[Las Rozas CF|Las Rozas]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[Real Aranjuez CF|Aranjuez]]\n| managerclubs4 = [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs5 = [[Club Bol\u00edvar|Bol\u00edvar]]\n| managerclubs6 = [[UE Lleida|Lleida]]\n| managerclubs7 = [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]]\n| managerclubs8 = [[Sporting Gij\u00f3n]]\n| managerclubs9 = [[Club Bol\u00edvar|Bol\u00edvar]]\n| managerclubs10 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs11 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| managerclubs12 = [[CD Tenerife|Tenerife]]\n| managerclubs13 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs14 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]\n| managerclubs15 = [[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs16 = [[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]]\n| managerclubs17 = [[Bidvest Wits F.C.|Bidvest Wits]]\n| managerclubs18 = [[ATK (football club)|ATK]]\n| managerclubs19 = [[FC Pune City|Pune City]]\n| managerclubs20 = [[ATK (football club)|ATK]]\n}}\n'''Antonio L\u00f3pez Habas''' (born 28 May 1957) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]], and the current [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of Indian club [[ATK (football club)|ATK]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Pozoblanco]], [[Province of C\u00f3rdoba (Spain)|C\u00f3rdoba]], L\u00f3pez had an unassuming career as a professional footballer, appearing in 48 [[La Liga]] matches over four seasons, eight of those for [[Sevilla FC]] to where he arrived in 1977 from local amateurs [[CD Pozoblanco]], first being assigned to [[Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico]].\n\nHe also represented [[Real Murcia]], [[Burgos CF (I)|Burgos CF]] and [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] (no appearances for the latter), retiring from the game at only 29 years of age. In [[1981\u201382 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1981\u201382]] he scored an astonishing 13 goals in 32 games for Burgos,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1981/11/12/pagina-18/1068857/pdf.html|title=3\u20130: No fue rival el Oviedo para el Burgos|trans-title=3\u20130: Burgos no match for Oviedo|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=J.A.|last=Paramo|language=Spanish|date=12 November 1981|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1981/12/21/pagina-15/1077240/pdf.html|title=Burgos 2, \u2013 M\u00e1laga 0|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=J.A.|last=Paramo|language=Spanish|date=21 December 1981|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1982/04/05/pagina-15/1084064/pdf.html|title=5\u20133: \u00a1Como un torrente!|trans-title=5\u20133: Like a tornado!|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Emilio|last=Rey|language=Spanish|date=5 April 1982|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> which nonetheless suffered [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] relegation due to financial irregularities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1982/07/12/pagina-26/1085383/pdf.html|title=Burgos, un club al borde de la bancarrota|trans-title=Burgos, a club on the verge of bankruptcy|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|language=Spanish|date=12 July 1982|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nL\u00f3pez started coaching in the early 1990s, with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|Atl\u00e9tico's reserves]]. After one season apiece in amateur football, also in the [[Community of Madrid|Madrid area]], he took charge of the [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia national team]], first as an assistant of [[Xabier Azkargorta]], and eventually appeared with it them as head coach at two [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] tournaments. He then returned to club action with [[Club Bol\u00edvar]], followed by a spell in his homeland with [[UE Lleida]], in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division]] \u2013 whilst at the [[Catalonia|Catalan]] side, he briefly accumulated with his work as the national coach of the [[South America]]n country, which he left for good in 1997.<ref name=LVG>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/deportes/2008/03/11/estudioso-teoria-futbol-sobrada-experiencia-banquillos-titular/00031205191605925677251.htm|title=Un estudioso de la teor\u00eda del f\u00fatbol con sobrada experiencia en los banquillos como titular|trans-title=A scholar of the football theory with head coach experience to spare|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|language=Spanish|date=11 March 2008|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n===Sporting Gij\u00f3n===\nIn 1998 after the bolivia national team management he return to spain as the manager of Sporting Gij\u00f3n in 1998-1999 season. After few matches he resigned the post in october 1998.<ref>[http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1998/10/06/pagina-28/397403/pdf.html Directiva y t\u00e9cnico, a la calle (Board and manager, fired)]; El Mundo Deportivo, 6 October 1998 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n===Valencia===\nThree years after his last job, with [[Club Bol\u00edvar]], L\u00f3pez was hired by [[Valencia CF]] as assistant to [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]]. After two season he appointed as the [[Valencia CF]] academy director.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/interviews/Sacking-Rafael-Benitez-was-a-mistake-Habas/articleshow/50477422.cms|title=Sacking Rafael Benitez was a mistake: Habas|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|last=Mukherjee|first=Debayan|date=7 January 2016|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> However, after the sacking of Italian [[Claudio Ranieri]], he managed the first team for 14 games as the ''Che'', the [[2003\u201304 La Liga|previous league champions]], eventually [[2004\u201305 La Liga|finished seventh]].<ref name=LVG/> Additionally, he worked at the [[Mestalla Stadium]] as youth system coordinator.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.ar/nota?id=304423|title=Llega un bombero con agua fresca|trans-title=Fireman arrives with fresh water|publisher=[[ESPN]]|language=Spanish|date=25 February 2005|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n===Tenerife===\nL\u00f3pez became [[CD Tenerife]]'s second head coach of [[2005\u201306 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following campaign]] in November 2005,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eldia.es/jornada/2005-11-15/9-LOPEZ-aqui-ahora.htm|title=L\u00d3PEZ, \"aqu\u00ed y ahora\"|trans-title=L\u00d3PEZ, \"here and now\"|newspaper=[[El D\u00eda (Canary Islands)|El D\u00eda]]|language=Spanish|date=15 November 2005|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref> being fired himself after only six second level matches. Two years later, he joined as [[Hristo Stoichkov]] assistant at [[RC Celta de Vigo]] after the depature of him habas stay at the  [[Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro]]'s staff at [[RC Celta de Vigo]] in the same tier. With the [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicians]] constantly battling relegation until the last month of [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|competition]], he was named [[Interim management|interim coach]] for the final three months<ref name=LVG/> as the team eventually managed to stay afloat; he was the third manager for the club in approximately one year.\n===Mamelodi Sundowns===\nIn June 2009  he joined south african club [[Mamelodi Sundowns F.C.|Mamelodi Sundowns]] as an assistant of [[Hristo Stoichkov]] and after departure of him he appointed as the head coach the team for [[2010\u201311 Premier Soccer League|2010\u20132011]] season and he resigned the post in february due to personal reasons.\n===Target Academy===\nIn January 2012, L\u00f3pez was appointed director of the Target Football Academy in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306193716/http://www.targetfootballacademy.com/staff.php|title=Staff - Target Football Academy|date=2012-03-06|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\n===Bidvest Wits===\nOn 13 July he signed for [[South Africa]]n club [[Bidvest Wits F.C.|Bidvest Wits FC]], agreeing to a two-year contract<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supersport.com/football/absa-premiership/news/120712/Wits_name_Lopez_as_new_coach|title=Wits name Lopez as new coach|publisher=[[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|SuperSport]]|date=12 July 2012|accessdate=12 July 2012}}</ref> but leaving on 4 January of the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/32074/clive-barker-replaces-antonio-lopez-habas-at-bidvest-wits|title=Barker replaces Habas at Wits|publisher=Kick Off|date=4 January 2013|accessdate=4 January 2013}}</ref>\n===Atl\u00e9tico Madrid===\nIn 2013 he joined as the director of [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]  technical academy in madrid. He reamained there for august 2014 when he was appointed as the head coach of indian club [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] which is co-owned by Ateltico Madrid<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.atleticodemadrid.com/noticias/antonio-lopez-were-calm-and-ready-to-face-the-challenge-of-the-super-league|title=Club Atl\u00e9tico de Madrid \u00b7 Web oficial - Antonio L\u00f3pez: \"We\u2019re calm and ready to face the challenge of the Super League\"|website=en.atleticodemadrid.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\n===ATK===\nIn August 2014, L\u00f3pez was named coach of [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] in the [[Indian Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/7083/isl/2014/08/01/4997270/atletico-de-kolkata-hire-deshi-bhaktawer-as-their|title=Atletico de Kolkata hire Deshi Bhaktawer as their goalkeeping coach|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|last=Bera|first=Kaustav|date=1 August 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> On 25 October he was given a four-match suspension and fined {{INR|5,00,000}} for his involvement in a spat with [[FC Goa]]'s [[Robert Pires]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/773-isl-announces-ruling-on-incidents-from-fc-goa-vs-atletico-de-kolkata-fixture|title=ISL announces ruling on incidents from FC Goa vs Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata fixture|publisher=[[Indian Super League]]|date=25 October 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> which was reduced to two upon appeal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/aiff-reduces-ban-on-atletico-de-kolkata-coach-antonio-lopez-habas/|title=AIFF reduces ban on Atletico de Kolkata coach Antonio Lopez Habas|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=31 October 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter a dip in form from midway through [[2014 Indian Super League season|the season]], L\u00f3pez led his team to [[2014 Indian Super League finals|the semi-finals]] by drawing with Goa,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/indian-super-league-2014/news/234371-isl-atletico-de-kolkata-sneak-into-semifinals-after-fikru-teferra-s-equaliser|title=ISL: Atletico de Kolkata sneak into semifinals after Fikru Teferra's equaliser|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> meeting the same opponent once again and defeating them on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/isl-live-fc-goa-vs-atletico-de-kolkata-semifinal-2nd-leg/1/407359.html|title=ISL: Atletico de Kolkata beat FC Goa on penalties to enter final|publisher=[[India Today]]|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> In [[2014 Indian Super League Final|the decisive match]], against [[Kerala Blasters FC]], he benched marquee player [[Luis Garcia (footballer, born 1978)|Luis Garc\u00eda]] and also-compatriot [[Jofre]], for which he was praised by critics,<ref>{{cite journal|title=\u0986\u09ae\u09bf  \u09b9\u09be\u09ac\u09be\u09b8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09b8 \u09a6\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u09a4\u09c7  \u09aa\u09be\u09b0\u09a4\u09be\u09ae \u09a8\u09be|trans-title=|publisher=\u0986\u09a8\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6 \u09ac\u09be\u099c\u09be\u09b0 \u09aa\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u0995\u09be|page=19|date=21 December 2014}}</ref> and the side won thanks to a goal by [[Mohammed Rafique (footballer)|Mohammed Rafique]] in [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/1850-substitute-mohammed-rafique-hands-atletico-de-kolkata-the-title|title=Substitute Mohammed Rafique hands Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata the title|publisher=Indian Super League|date=20 December 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n===Pune City===\nOn 25 April 2016, L\u00f3pez was appointed at fellow league club [[FC Pune City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goalie365.com/show_details.php?article_id=568|title=FC Pune City appoints Habas as head coach|publisher=Goalie 365|date=25 April 2016|accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref> On 16 September 2017, after a run-in with the board of directors, he left his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indianfootballfans.org/fc-pune-city-coach-antonio-habas-exist-club/|title=FC Pune City head coach Antonio Habas got suspended: ISL news 2017|publisher=Indian Football Fans|date=16 September 2017|accessdate=16 September 2017}}</ref>\n===ATK===\nIn May 2019, L\u00f3pez returned to ATK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ATKFC/status/1123884603784216577|title=Guess who's back??!!!|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=2 May 2019|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref> On 14 March 2020, in [[2020 Indian Super League Final|a final]] played behind closed doors, he won the national championship against [[Chennaiyin FC]] to become the first manager to achieve the feat twice with the same team.<ref name=ISL>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/atk-best-chennaiyin-in-hero-isl-2019-20-final-to-clinch-record-third-title|title=ATK best Chennaiyin in Hero ISL 2019\u201320 final to clinch record third title|publisher=Indian Super League|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/antonio-habas-my-special-connection-with-atk-continues|title=Antonio Habas: My special connection with ATK continues|publisher=Indian Super League|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Murcia'''\n*[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]: [[1982\u201383 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1982\u201383]]\n'''Ateltico Madrid'''\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Super cup]]: [[1985 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Bolivia'''\n*[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] runner-up: [[1997 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1997]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.la-razon.com/marcas/Antonio-Lopez-problemas-llegas-debil_0_2338566121.html|title=Antonio L\u00f3pez: \u2018Mientras m\u00e1s problemas hay, llegas m\u00e1s d\u00e9bil\u2019|trans-title=Antonio L\u00f3pez: \u2018The more problems there are, the weaker you arrive\u2019|newspaper=[[La Raz\u00f3n (La Paz)|La Raz\u00f3n]]|last=Semp\u00e9rtegui|first=Rafael|language=Spanish|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Atl\u00e9tico Kolkata'''\n*[[Indian Super League]]: [[2014 Indian Super League season|2014]], [[2019\u201320 Indian Super League season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=ISL/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|3545|Antonio L\u00f3pez}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|3545|Antonio L\u00f3pez}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120306193716/http://www.targetfootballacademy.com/staff.php Target Academy profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160812113527/http://antoniolopezhabas.com/ Official website]\n\n{{ATK (football club) squad}}\n{{Indian Super League head coaches}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Bolivia squads\n|bg = green\n|fg = White\n|list1=\n{{Bolivia Squad 1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Bolivia Squad 1997 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Antonio L\u00f3pez managerial positions\n|list1= \n{{Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B managers}}\n{{UE Lleida managers}}\n{{Sporting de Gij\u00f3n managers}}\n{{Valencia CF managers}}\n{{CD Tenerife managers}}\n{{Celta de Vigo managers}}\n{{Club Bol\u00edvar managers}}\n{{ATK (football club) managers}}\n{{FC Pune City managers}}\n{{Bolivia national football team managers}}\n}}\n{{Indian Super League winning managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lopez Habas, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Andalusian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico players]]\n[[Category:Sevilla FC players]]\n[[Category:Burgos CF (I) footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Murcia players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B managers]]\n[[Category:UE Lleida managers]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n managers]]\n[[Category:Valencia CF managers]]\n[[Category:CD Tenerife managers]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo managers]]\n[[Category:Mamelodi Sundowns F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League head coaches]]\n[[Category:ATK (football club) head coaches]]\n[[Category:Bolivia national football team managers]]\n[[Category:1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica managers]]\n[[Category:1997 Copa Am\u00e9rica managers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer managers in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in India]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish football player/manager}}\n{{spanish name 2|L\u00f3pez|Habas}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Antonio Habas\n| image =Antonio L\u00f3pez Habas.jpg\n| caption =\n| fullname = Antonio L\u00f3pez Habas\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|5|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Pozoblanco]], Spain\n| height = {{convert|1.70|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] (manager)\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1976\u20131977\n| years2 = 1977\u20131978\n| years3 = 1978\u20131980\n| years4 = 1980\u20131982\n| years5 = 1982\u20131985\n| years6 = 1985\u20131986\n| clubs1 = [[CD Pozoblanco|Pozoblanco]]\n| clubs2 = [[Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico|Sevilla B]]\n| clubs3 = [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]\n| clubs4 = [[Burgos CF (I)|Burgos]]\n| clubs5 = [[Real Murcia|Murcia]]\n| clubs6 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| caps1 =\n| caps2 =\n| caps3 = 8\n| caps4 = 45\n| caps5 = 74\n| caps6 = 0\n| totalcaps = \n| goals1 =\n| goals2 =\n| goals3 = 0\n| goals4 = 14\n| goals5 = 11\n| goals6 = 0\n| totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 =\n| nationalcaps1 =\n| nationalgoals1 =\n| manageryears1 = 1990\u20131991\n| manageryears2 = 1991\u20131992\n| manageryears3 = 1992\u20131993\n| manageryears4 = 1993\u20131994\n| manageryears5 = 1994\u20131995\n| manageryears6 = 1995\u20131996\n| manageryears7 = 1995\u20131997\n| manageryears8 = 1998\n| manageryears9 = 2000\u20132001\n| manageryears10 = 2001\u20132003\n| manageryears11 = 2005\n| manageryears12 = 2005\n| manageryears13 = 2007\u20132008\n| manageryears14 = 2008\n| manageryears15 = 2010\u20132011\n| manageryears16 = 2012\u20132013\n| manageryears17 = 2014\u20132016\n| manageryears18 = 2016\u20132017\n| manageryears19 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|Atl\u00e9tico Madrile\u00f1o]]\n| managerclubs2 = [[Las Rozas CF|Las Rozas]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[Real Aranjuez CF|Aranjuez]]\n| managerclubs4 = [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs5 = [[Club Bol\u00edvar|Bol\u00edvar]]\n| managerclubs6 = [[UE Lleida|Lleida]]\n| managerclubs7 = [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]]\n| managerclubs8 = [[Sporting Gij\u00f3n]]\n| managerclubs9 = [[Club Bol\u00edvar|Bol\u00edvar]]\n| managerclubs10 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs11 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| managerclubs12 = [[CD Tenerife|Tenerife]]\n| managerclubs13 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] (assistant)\n| managerclubs14 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]\n| managerclubs15 = [[Mamelodi Sundowns]]\n| managerclubs16 = [[Bidvest Wits F.C.|Bidvest Wits]]\n| managerclubs17 = [[ATK (football club)|ATK]]\n| managerclubs18 = [[FC Pune City|Pune City]]\n| managerclubs19 = [[ATK (football club)|ATK]]\n}}\n'''Antonio L\u00f3pez Habas''' (born 28 May 1957) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]], and the current [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of Indian club [[ATK (football club)|ATK]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Pozoblanco]], [[Province of C\u00f3rdoba (Spain)|C\u00f3rdoba]], L\u00f3pez had an unassuming career as a professional footballer, appearing in 48 [[La Liga]] matches over four seasons, eight of those for [[Sevilla FC]] to where he arrived in 1977 from local amateurs [[CD Pozoblanco]], first being assigned to [[Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico]].\n\nHe also represented [[Real Murcia]], [[Burgos CF (I)|Burgos CF]] and [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] (no appearances for the latter), retiring from the game at only 29 years of age. In [[1981\u201382 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1981\u201382]] he scored an astonishing 13 goals in 32 games for Burgos,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1981/11/12/pagina-18/1068857/pdf.html|title=3\u20130: No fue rival el Oviedo para el Burgos|trans-title=3\u20130: Burgos no match for Oviedo|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=J.A.|last=Paramo|language=Spanish|date=12 November 1981|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1981/12/21/pagina-15/1077240/pdf.html|title=Burgos 2, \u2013 M\u00e1laga 0|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=J.A.|last=Paramo|language=Spanish|date=21 December 1981|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1982/04/05/pagina-15/1084064/pdf.html|title=5\u20133: \u00a1Como un torrente!|trans-title=5\u20133: Like a tornado!|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Emilio|last=Rey|language=Spanish|date=5 April 1982|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref> which nonetheless suffered [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] relegation due to financial irregularities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1982/07/12/pagina-26/1085383/pdf.html|title=Burgos, un club al borde de la bancarrota|trans-title=Burgos, a club on the verge of bankruptcy|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|language=Spanish|date=12 July 1982|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nL\u00f3pez started coaching in the early 1990s, with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B|Atl\u00e9tico's reserves]]. After one season apiece in amateur football, also in the [[Community of Madrid|Madrid area]], he took charge of the [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia national team]], first as an assistant, and eventually appeared with it them as head coach at two [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] tournaments. He then returned to club action with [[Club Bol\u00edvar]], followed by a spell in his homeland with [[UE Lleida]], in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division]] \u2013 whilst at the [[Catalonia|Catalan]] side, he briefly accumulated with his work as the national coach of the [[South America]]n country, which he left for good in 1997.<ref name=LVG>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/deportes/2008/03/11/estudioso-teoria-futbol-sobrada-experiencia-banquillos-titular/00031205191605925677251.htm|title=Un estudioso de la teor\u00eda del f\u00fatbol con sobrada experiencia en los banquillos como titular|trans-title=A scholar of the football theory with head coach experience to spare|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|language=Spanish|date=11 March 2008|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThree years after his last job, with [[Club Bol\u00edvar]], L\u00f3pez was hired by [[Valencia CF]] as assistant to [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/interviews/Sacking-Rafael-Benitez-was-a-mistake-Habas/articleshow/50477422.cms|title=Sacking Rafael Benitez was a mistake: Habas|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|last=Mukherjee|first=Debayan|date=7 January 2016|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> However, after the sacking of Italian [[Claudio Ranieri]], he managed the first team for 14 games as the ''Che'', the [[2003\u201304 La Liga|previous league champions]], eventually [[2004\u201305 La Liga|finished seventh]].<ref name=LVG/> Additionally, he worked at the [[Mestalla Stadium]] as youth system coordinator.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.ar/nota?id=304423|title=Llega un bombero con agua fresca|trans-title=Fireman arrives with fresh water|publisher=[[ESPN]]|language=Spanish|date=25 February 2005|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nL\u00f3pez became [[CD Tenerife]]'s second head coach of [[2005\u201306 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following campaign]] in November 2005,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eldia.es/jornada/2005-11-15/9-LOPEZ-aqui-ahora.htm|title=L\u00d3PEZ, \"aqu\u00ed y ahora\"|trans-title=L\u00d3PEZ, \"here and now\"|newspaper=[[El D\u00eda (Canary Islands)|El D\u00eda]]|language=Spanish|date=15 November 2005|accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref> being fired himself after only six second level matches. Two years later, he joined [[Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro]]'s staff at [[RC Celta de Vigo]] in the same tier. With the [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicians]] constantly battling relegation until the last month of [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|competition]], he was named [[Interim management|interim coach]] for the final three months<ref name=LVG/> as the team eventually managed to stay afloat; he was the third manager for the club in approximately one year.\n\nIn January 2012, L\u00f3pez was appointed director of the Target Football Academy in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]. On 13 July he signed for [[South Africa]]n club [[Bidvest Wits F.C.|Bidvest Wits FC]], agreeing to a two-year contract<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supersport.com/football/absa-premiership/news/120712/Wits_name_Lopez_as_new_coach|title=Wits name Lopez as new coach|publisher=[[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|SuperSport]]|date=12 July 2012|accessdate=12 July 2012}}</ref> but leaving on 4 January of the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kickoff.com/news/32074/clive-barker-replaces-antonio-lopez-habas-at-bidvest-wits|title=Barker replaces Habas at Wits|publisher=Kick Off|date=4 January 2013|accessdate=4 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, L\u00f3pez was named coach of [[ATK (football club)|ATK]] in the [[Indian Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/7083/isl/2014/08/01/4997270/atletico-de-kolkata-hire-deshi-bhaktawer-as-their|title=Atletico de Kolkata hire Deshi Bhaktawer as their goalkeeping coach|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|last=Bera|first=Kaustav|date=1 August 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> On 25 October he was given a four-match suspension and fined {{INR|5,00,000}} for his involvement in a spat with [[FC Goa]]'s [[Robert Pires]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/773-isl-announces-ruling-on-incidents-from-fc-goa-vs-atletico-de-kolkata-fixture|title=ISL announces ruling on incidents from FC Goa vs Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata fixture|publisher=[[Indian Super League]]|date=25 October 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> which was reduced to two upon appeal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/aiff-reduces-ban-on-atletico-de-kolkata-coach-antonio-lopez-habas/|title=AIFF reduces ban on Atletico de Kolkata coach Antonio Lopez Habas|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=31 October 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter a dip in form from midway through [[2014 Indian Super League season|the season]], L\u00f3pez led his team to [[2014 Indian Super League finals|the semi-finals]] by drawing with Goa,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/indian-super-league-2014/news/234371-isl-atletico-de-kolkata-sneak-into-semifinals-after-fikru-teferra-s-equaliser|title=ISL: Atletico de Kolkata sneak into semifinals after Fikru Teferra's equaliser|publisher=[[NDTV]]|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> meeting the same opponent once again and defeating them on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/isl-live-fc-goa-vs-atletico-de-kolkata-semifinal-2nd-leg/1/407359.html|title=ISL: Atletico de Kolkata beat FC Goa on penalties to enter final|publisher=[[India Today]]|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref> In [[2014 Indian Super League Final|the decisive match]], against [[Kerala Blasters FC]], he benched marquee player [[Luis Garcia (footballer, born 1978)|Luis Garc\u00eda]] and also-compatriot [[Jofre]], for which he was praised by critics,<ref>{{cite journal|title=\u0986\u09ae\u09bf  \u09b9\u09be\u09ac\u09be\u09b8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09b8 \u09a6\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u09a4\u09c7  \u09aa\u09be\u09b0\u09a4\u09be\u09ae \u09a8\u09be|trans-title=|publisher=\u0986\u09a8\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6 \u09ac\u09be\u099c\u09be\u09b0 \u09aa\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u0995\u09be|page=19|date=21 December 2014}}</ref> and the side won thanks to a goal by [[Mohammed Rafique (footballer)|Mohammed Rafique]] in [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/1850-substitute-mohammed-rafique-hands-atletico-de-kolkata-the-title|title=Substitute Mohammed Rafique hands Atl\u00e9tico de Kolkata the title|publisher=Indian Super League|date=20 December 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 April 2016, L\u00f3pez was appointed at fellow league club [[FC Pune City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goalie365.com/show_details.php?article_id=568|title=FC Pune City appoints Habas as head coach|publisher=Goalie 365|date=25 April 2016|accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref> On 16 September 2017, after a run-in with the board of directors, he left his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indianfootballfans.org/fc-pune-city-coach-antonio-habas-exist-club/|title=FC Pune City head coach Antonio Habas got suspended: ISL news 2017|publisher=Indian Football Fans|date=16 September 2017|accessdate=16 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, L\u00f3pez returned to ATK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ATKFC/status/1123884603784216577|title=Guess who's back??!!!|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=2 May 2019|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref> On 14 March 2020, in [[2020 Indian Super League Final|a final]] played behind closed doors, he won the national championship against [[Chennaiyin FC]] to become the first manager to achieve the feat twice with the same team.<ref name=ISL>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/atk-best-chennaiyin-in-hero-isl-2019-20-final-to-clinch-record-third-title|title=ATK best Chennaiyin in Hero ISL 2019\u201320 final to clinch record third title|publisher=Indian Super League|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/antonio-habas-my-special-connection-with-atk-continues|title=Antonio Habas: My special connection with ATK continues|publisher=Indian Super League|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Murcia'''\n*[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]: [[1982\u201383 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1982\u201383]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Bolivia'''\n*[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] runner-up: [[1997 Copa Am\u00e9rica|1997]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.la-razon.com/marcas/Antonio-Lopez-problemas-llegas-debil_0_2338566121.html|title=Antonio L\u00f3pez: \u2018Mientras m\u00e1s problemas hay, llegas m\u00e1s d\u00e9bil\u2019|trans-title=Antonio L\u00f3pez: \u2018The more problems there are, the weaker you arrive\u2019|newspaper=[[La Raz\u00f3n (La Paz)|La Raz\u00f3n]]|last=Semp\u00e9rtegui|first=Rafael|language=Spanish|date=4 September 2015|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Atl\u00e9tico Kolkata'''\n*[[Indian Super League]]: [[2014 Indian Super League season|2014]], [[2019\u201320 Indian Super League season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=ISL/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|3545|Antonio L\u00f3pez}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|3545|Antonio L\u00f3pez}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120306193716/http://www.targetfootballacademy.com/staff.php Target Academy profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160812113527/http://antoniolopezhabas.com/ Official website]\n\n{{ATK (football club) squad}}\n{{Indian Super League head coaches}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Bolivia squads\n|bg = green\n|fg = White\n|list1=\n{{Bolivia Squad 1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Bolivia Squad 1997 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Antonio L\u00f3pez managerial positions\n|list1= \n{{Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B managers}}\n{{UE Lleida managers}}\n{{Sporting de Gij\u00f3n managers}}\n{{Valencia CF managers}}\n{{CD Tenerife managers}}\n{{Celta de Vigo managers}}\n{{Club Bol\u00edvar managers}}\n{{ATK (football club) managers}}\n{{FC Pune City managers}}\n{{Bolivia national football team managers}}\n}}\n{{Indian Super League winning managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lopez Habas, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Andalusian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Sevilla Atl\u00e9tico players]]\n[[Category:Sevilla FC players]]\n[[Category:Burgos CF (I) footballers]]\n[[Category:Real Murcia players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Madrid B managers]]\n[[Category:UE Lleida managers]]\n[[Category: